\begin_layout Title
Designing Effective and Inclusive ICT-mediated Agricultural Information
 Campaigns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Bjorn Van Campenhout, Els Lecoutere, and David J Spielman
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
In programs to disseminate information through agricultural extension and
 advisory services, seemingly small design attributes—the way the information
 is delivered, who delivers the information, or who is targeted by the message—c
an result in significant differences in effectiveness and inclusiveness
 of the intervention.
 Information and communications technology (ICT) can reduce the costs associated
 with adapting design attributes to particular problems and contexts.
 This study compares the effectiveness of different ICT enabled technologies
 to provide agricultural extension information to smallholder farmers.
 In addition, it assesses the role of the gender composition of the person(s)
 who provide(s) the information and the gender composition of the person(s)
 who receive(s) the information in making video-mediated extension campaigns
 more inclusive.
 Through field experiments among smallholder maize farmers in Uganda, the
 effectiveness of changing these design attributes—technology, messenger,
 and recipient— is assessed by measuring knowledge gained, adoption of modern
 inputs and recommend practices, maize production and disposal, and well-being.
 we further investigate how the interventions affect gender disaggregated
 outcomes, such as adoption and production on male, female and jointly managed
 plots, as well as intra-household decision making.
 We find that short extension video messages increase knowledge, technology
 adoption, and production at the household level.
 We find that a technology that is more demand driven further increases
 productivity, as farmers use it to obtain additional information on more
 complex technologies such as hybrid seed.
 Showing extension videos also to women instead of only to men increases
 women knowledge, boosting their confidence and leading to more consultation
 among spouses.
 If women receive information, they make decisions (and adopt recommended
 technologies) on more plots, significantly increasing their role in maize
 production.
 However, this effect disappears if men also receive this information.
 Changing the messenger attribute does not have any effect.
\end_layout

