\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These hypotheses are tested using a field experiment in which smallholder
 farm households are randomly assigned to a group that receives a particular
 information intervention, and their outcomes are compared to the outcomes
 of a group of farm households that did not receive that particular information
 intervention 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de2016field"

\end_inset

.
 As we want to test more than one research hypothesis and are particularly
 interested in comparing the relative effectiveness of various attributes
 of an ICT-mediated extension approach, we opt for a factorial design.
 Generally, in factorial designs, a smaller sample size is needed to answer
 a fixed number of research questions as opposed to parallel designs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We work with 3,600 farm households sampled from the population of dual household
s cultivating maize across five districts of eastern Uganda.
 The core information interventions take the form of short videos that explain
 simple, yet effective, ways to increase maize productivity and profitability,
 such as best practices in row spacing, the importance of quality seed,
 optimal soil fertility management, and farm budget management.
 To test overall effectiveness of the information provided through the video,
 we compare outcomes of farm households that were exposed to a placebo video
 to outcomes of farm households that were shown the video.
 To about two third of the sample of farm households that were shown the
 agricultural information video, we also provided access to an IVR system,
 consisting of a toll free phone number and a leaflet explaining that they
 could call this number any time if they needed more information on maize
 farming.
 Finally, we sent eight sms messages at strategic points in time to half
 of the sample of households that got the IVR number (and thus were also
 shown the video) reminding them about the importance of a particular technology
 or practice that was explained in the video and repeating that they can
 always call the IVR system if they want more information.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To test how information asymmetry within the household affects decision
 making and outcomes, we compare farm households where the video was shown
 only to the man in the household (the status quo) with households where
 the video was shown only to the woman in the household, and with households
 where the video was shown to man and women together as a couple.
 To test the hypothesis on the importance of the gender (composition) of
 the person(s) providing the information, we produced different versions
 of the video.
 In each version of the video, the information content was exactly the same,
 only the person (or persons) that featured in the video was changed.
 In one version of the video, all the information is provided by an individual
 male farmer, while in a second version of the video, the information is
 given by a female farmer.
 In a third version of the video, the exact same information is given by
 a couple, each spouse taking turns in explaining things.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the farm household level, we find that providing information to farm
 households through short video messages increases their knowledge about
 modern inputs, improved technologies, and recommended practices.
 In addition, farm households who were shown the video are also more likely
 to adopt a range of inputs, technologies, and practices that were presented
 in the videos.
 We also find clear effects on production with maize yields 14 percent higher
 than in control households.
 However, these results do not translate into higher well-being.
 The IVR has no additional knowledge impact.
 The additional effect on technology adoption of IVR is also less important:
 we only find a positive effect on the uptake of hybrid seed.
 Still, we do find that households that were allocated to the IVR treatment
 report yields that are 8 percent higher.
 The sms campaign has no additional impact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With respect to the recipient of the information, there are some household
 level effects.
 However, household level effects may mask opposite effects at the individual
 level.
 We find that if the video is shown to the couple or the woman (as opposed
 to only the man), knowledge of the woman increases significantly, suggesting
 information does not flow efficiently from the man to the woman within
 the household.
 When the video was shown to couple (as opposed to only the man), women
 are more likely to speak up if they do not agree, and it is more likely
 that an agreement between spouses is reached.
 If women also receive information, men are less likely to make adoption
 decisions by themselves.
 Women, on the other hand, will make significantly more decisions on the
 use of improved agronomic practices and inputs, but only if this information
 is not also available to the husband.
 If only women receive information, they adopt more than if only men receive
 the information.
 As a result, we find that including women in receiving extension information
 increases the role of women in maize production.
 We do not find that it matters if the information in the video was provided
 by a man, a woman, or a man and woman together.
\end_layout

