\begin_layout Standard
Second, we address the persistent issue of gender bias in the provision
 of agricultural extension services and the dissemination of information
 to smallholder farmers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doss200127,FLETSCHNER20111422,peterman2011understanding,QUISUMBING2010581"

\end_inset

.
 Often, extension agents are male, and their default strategy for disseminating
 information on crop management is to target one decision-maker in a household,
 which is generally the man in dual households.
 The assumption that extension messages targeting one household member will
 spread to other household members—including women and youth —may be false
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:fpr:ifprid:1411"

\end_inset

.
 Men do not necessarily discuss production decisions or share information
 with women household members, especially if extension messages focus on
 men's priorities and crops 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fletschner2011gender"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, evidence suggests that in certain contexts, gender homophily
 effects in which men learn more from other men and women learn more from
 other women, may dominate other intra-household information-sharing effects
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doss200127"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, we explore this issue further by investigating the extent to which
 farms are managed at the household level in a cooperative manner, e.g., through
 joint decision-making between and among male and female co-heads of the
 household.
 This expands on recent advances in the measurement of gendered dimensions
 of empowerment, including decison-making power, intra-household distribution
 of decision-making power and control over income and resources 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ALKIRE201371,MAHMUD2012610"

\end_inset

.
 We further examine if women's involvement in maize farming can be increased
 by questioning cultural norms and influencing aspirations 
