\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\series bold
The impact of ICT-mediated agronomic extension information on production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We next turn to changes in production related outcome as a result of our
 experiment providing ICT-mediated agronomic extension information using
 different dissemination technologies.
 We first look at maize production aggregated at the household level.
 During the endline survey, we asked both spouses separately to estimate
 how much maize was harvested from each plot owned by their household.
 These quantities were then summed over the different household maize plots
 for each spouse and the average between the two spouses was taken as the
 final estimate of household level maize production.
 We find that, overall, a typical farm household in our sample produced
 about 460 kg of maize in the second season of 2017 (first column in Table
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:yield_ag_allh"

\end_inset

).
 Households produced this on 1.13 acres on average.
 Taken together, we find that yields, defined as kilograms per acre, amounted
 to on average 470 kg per acre.
 This is much higher than yields recorded at baseline (290 kg/acre) for
 the first season of 2017 , as this season there was more and more regular
 rainfall and there was increased attention for strategies to combat fall
 armyworm.
 Still, compared to FAOSTAT figures (1000 kg/acre) or figures from the Uganda
 household survey data (typically around 600 kg/acre), yields were below
 normal, as is also confirmed by the fact that in only 40 percent of households
 at least one spouse reported that yields were better than a typical year
 on at least one plot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Columns 2 and 3 in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:yield_ag_allh"

\end_inset

 report results for the impact of the different dissemination technologies
 with respect to outcomes related to production.
 In the top panel we again compare outcomes of control households having
 seen the placebo video to outcomes of households that were shown the interventi
on video.
 Household level production, expressed in logs and trimmed 5 percent, does
 not differ between the two groups.
 We do find, however, that households that were exposed to the agricultural
 extension video seemed to cultivate smaller plots.
 Their reported acreage is 11 percent smaller than among control households
 .
 However, the difference is not significant at the 5 percent level after
 controlling for FWER.
 The fact that the same amount is cultivated on a smaller area also resulted
 in the fact that in households that were shown an intervention video, yields
 were 14 percent higher than in control households.
 As mean productivity in control households was 428 kg/acre, this means
 mean productivity among households where the video was shown was about
 488 kg/acre.
 Further, in about 38.7 percent of households in the control group, at least
 one spouse indicates that yields were better than in a normal year on at
 least one plot.
 This is 2.7 percentage points higher among households that saw a video,
 but the difference is not significant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall, we find that the video information intervention versus a placebo
 video had a significant and positive effect on production outcomes, as
 is evident from the positive treatment effect of the production index,
