\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we look at the impact of the different information interventions
 on measures of well-being at the household level.
 Welfare is captured though self-assessment, as well as through consumption.
 We have asked these questions only to the woman within the household, as
 we assume she has a better idea of consumption expenditures within the
 household and the general level of well-being.
 First, we asked if they feel their household is better off (as opposed
 to equally well off or worse off) in terms of income and consumption than
 the average households in their community.
 We find that among the control group that was shown the placebo video,
 about 40.1 percent of households felt they were better off than average
 (top panel in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
