 This percentage was slightly higher among households that received the
 intervention video , but the difference was not statistically significant.
 Similarly, we asked the woman in the household to indicate if she thought
 they were better off than six months ago.
 We find that among the households that did not get the agricultural extension
 video, 39.7 percent of households indicated they did better than half a
 year earlier, and this percentage was the same among the households that
 did get to see the intervention video.
 We also include two standard self assessed food security questions taken
 from the Household Food Insecurity Access Scale (HFIAS).
 We asked if households were generally able to eat their preferred food,
 and 42.6 percent of households responded affirmatively.
 We also asked if households were generally able to eat enough food and
 found this to be the case in almost 60 percent of baseline households.
 We found that, judged by these questions, the intervention video seemed
