Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a world characterized by incomplete and asymmetric information, and intra-hou
sehold gender related constraints to efficiency, targeted efforts to fill
 knowledge gaps can make a big difference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "banerjee2011poor,udry1996gender"

\end_inset

.
 However, not every information campaign is equally effective nor inclusive,
 and often, seemingly small attributes, such as the way it is delivered,
 who is targeted by the message and who delivers the message, can result
 in significant differences in impact at the household and intra-household
 level.
 Understanding and quantifying the importance of each of these design attributes
 through rigorous evaluation research should therefore be an essential part
 of any knowledge exchange model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In thus study, we evaluate the effectiveness of three complementary Information
 and Communication Technology (ICT) enabled agricultural information exchange
 approaches (short video messages, Interactive Voice Response (IVR) and
 sms campaigns) that can be brought to scale relatively easily and at significan
tly lower cost than alternative modes of agricultural extension information
 provision.
 In addition, and motivated by the observation that most agricultural advisory
 services are biased toward men, this study looked at two gender related
 attributes of a stylized ICT mediated agricultural extension information
 campaign.
 The first attribute is the gender composition of the person or persons
 to which the information is targeted.
 The second attribute consists of the gender composition of the person or
 persons that provide the information.
 This allows us to test three hypotheses related to (1) the effectiveness
 of the information intervention and the comparative effectiveness of different
 dissemination technologies (H1) (2) the role of information asymmetries
 within farming households (H2); and (3) the importance of role models and
 projecting a cooperative approach to farming (H3).

\emph on
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The various hypotheses are tested using a field experiment where the recipient
 of the information and the messenger of the information are randomly altered
 according to a 3 by 3 factorial design, in addition to a pure control group
 that was shown a placebo video.
 The study population are maize farm households in eastern Uganda, from
 which we sampled about 3,600 couples.
 These farm households were then shown a video with extension information
 according to the treatment group they were randomly assigned to.
 The videos showed how inputs and improved farming practices can be used
 to increase production.
 It also explains important concepts in inter-temporal decision making.
 The messages are also packaged in an attractive way, with role model farmers
 explaining how intensification of maize production improved their lives.
 The videos were shown twice, once just before the the planting season,
 and once during planting stage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that as a result of being shown the information video as compared
 to a placebo video, farmers have increased knowledge.
 We do not find incremental effects for the addition of IVR and sms reminders.
 As a result of being shown the intervention video, farmers also adopted
 a range of recommended practices.
 We also find that farmers reduce their use of DAP or NPK and increase adoption
 of Urea (and to a lesser extent inorganic fertilizer) to engage in more
 balanced soil nutrient management.
 Effects are less strong for adding IVR to the video treatment.
 However, there is some evidence that a demand driven information service
 such as IVR may be more effective to increase the adoption of more complex
 technologies (eg.
 basal application of DAP and hybrid maize seed).
 As a result of having been shown a video, households reduce the area under
 maize cultivation while producing the same amount, leading to a significant
 increase in maize yields, from 428 kg/acre to 488 kg/acre.
 Adding IVR further increases this to 526 kg/acre, but this is driven by
 an increase in production on the same area under cultivation.
 We find no effect from any intervention on self assessed well-being, nor
 on consumption expenditures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is some evidence that showing video only to the female co-head reduces
 household level knowledge as opposed to when the info is given to the man
 only.
 There is also some evidence that targeting the couple to view the intervention
 video instead of only the man leads to an increased likelihood of the use
 of fertilizer and that this fertilizer is also combined with improved seeds.
 Comparing male recipient households to households where the video was shown
 to the couple results in no differences in production related outcomes
 measured at the household level.
 Changing the messenger attribute does not have any effect on household
 level outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the video is shown to the couple or the woman in the household (as
 opposed to showing it to only the man), knowledge of the woman increases
 significantly, suggesting information does not flow from the man to the
 woman within the household.
 When the video was shown to couple (as opposed to only the man), women
 are more likely to speak up if they do not agree, and it is more likely
 that an agreement is reached.
 If women also receive the information (alone or as part of the couple),
 men are less likely to make adoption decisions unilaterally.
 If women also receive information, they will make significantly more decisions
 on the use of improved agronomic practices and inputs, but only if this
 information is not also available to the husband.
 Showing the video to both spouses jointly does seem to increase the likelihood
 of joint decision making for some practices, but none is significant after
 correcting for multiple comparisons.
 Finally, on an average plot of one acre, if the video was shown to a woman
 only, the amount produced per acre under male management reduces by 34
 kg and the amount under female management increases by about 26 kg.
 We do not find that it matters if the information in the video was provided
 by a man, a woman, or a man and woman together.
 
\end_layout

